<section xml:id="complex_plane_section"  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>
Complex Numbers
</title>

<p>
  Elements in the set of complex numbers <m>\C</m> are in one-to-one
 correspondence with points in the Cartesian plane <m>\R^2</m>.  We will
 write <m>z\leftrightarrow (x,y)</m> to denote that the complex number <m>z</m>
  corresponds to the ordered pair <m>(x,y)</m> in <m>\R^2</m>.
</p>

<p>
  Given a complex number <m>z</m> corresponding to the
  point <m>(x,y)=(r\cos \theta,r\sin \theta)</m> with <m>r\geq 0</m>,
  we say that <m>x</m> is the <term>real part</term><idx><h>real part
  of a complex number</h></idx>
   of <m>z</m>, and that <m>y</m> is the
  <term>imaginary part</term><idx><h>imaginary part of a complex number</h></idx>
  of <m>z</m>, denoted <m>\re(z)=x</m>,<notation><usage><m>\re(z)</m>
	        </usage>
    <description>real part of the complex number <m>z</m>
	 </description>
  </notation> and <m>\im(z)=y</m>,     <notation><usage><m>\im(z)</m>
	        </usage>
    <description>imaginary part of the complex number <m>z</m>
	 </description>
     </notation>
  respectively. We say that <m>r</m> is the <term>norm</term><idx><h>norm of a complex number</h></idx>
  or <term>modulus</term><idx><h>modulus of a complex number</h></idx>
  of <m>z</m>,  and we say
      that <m>\theta</m> is an <term>argument</term><idx><h>argument of a complex number</h></idx>
      of <m>z</m>, denoted <m>|z|=r</m><notation><usage><m>|z|</m>
    </usage><description>norm of the complex
    number <m>z</m></description></notation> and <m>\arg(z)=\theta</m><notation><usage><m>\arg(z)</m>
	</usage><description>argument of the complex
	  number <m>z</m>
    </description>
  </notation>, respectively.
</p>

<p>
  The set <m>\C</m> contains the set <m>\R</m> as a subset in the
 following way. The real number <m>x</m>, which is also the complex number
 <m>x</m>, corresponds to the ordered pair <m>(x,0)</m>.  A complex number that
  corresponds to an ordered pair <m>(0,y)</m> is called <term>(pure)
   imaginary</term><idx><h>pure imaginary number</h></idx>. The complex number that corresponds to the ordered pair
 <m>(0,1)</m> is called <m>i</m>     <notation><usage><m>i</m>
	        </usage>
   <description>the complex number <m>i</m>
	 </description>
     </notation>. The complex number 1 is the same as the real
 number 1 and corresponds to the point <m>(1,0)</m>, and the complex number 0
 is the same as the real number 0 and corresponds to the origin
 <m>(0,0)</m>.

</p>

<p>
  Let <m>z,w</m> be complex numbers, with corresponding Cartesian points
  <md>
    <mrow>z \amp \leftrightarrow (a,b)=(r\cos \theta,r\sin\theta)\amp \text{and}</mrow>
  <mrow>w\amp \leftrightarrow  (c,d)=(s\cos\phi,s\sin\phi)</mrow>
  </md>
  with <m>r,s\geq  0</m>.
  The <term>sum</term><idx><h>sum of two complex numbers</h></idx>
   of <m>z</m> and <m>w</m>, denoted <m>z+w</m>, is defined by
  <men xml:id="complexsum">z+w \leftrightarrow (a+c,b+d).</men>
  The <term>product</term><idx><h>product of two complex numbers</h></idx>
   of <m>z</m> and <m>w</m>,
denoted <m>zw</m>, is defined by
<men xml:id="complexproduct">zw \leftrightarrow 
  rs(\cos(\theta+\phi),\sin(\theta+\phi)).</men>
  If <m>\alpha</m> is real, then
  <xref ref="complexproduct"/> takes the following form.
<mdn><mrow xml:id="complexrealscaling">\alpha z \leftrightarrow 
    \alpha (a,b) \amp \amp (\alpha\in\R)</mrow></mdn>
</p>


<exercise xml:id="complexmultfirstexer"><statement><p>
      <ol>
	<li>Use definition <xref ref="complexproduct"/> to
	  multiply <m>-1</m> times <m>-1</m> as <em>complex
	  numbers</em>, that is, using <xref ref="complexproduct"/>.
	</li>
	<li>Use <xref ref="complexproduct"/> to show that <m>i^2=-1</m>.
	</li>
	<li>Use <xref ref="complexproduct"/> to prove <xref ref="complexrealscaling"/>.
	</li>	
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="complexmultfirstexer"/></title>
  <p>
    <ol>
      <li>The complex number <m>-1</m> corresponds to the
	point <m>(-1,0)=(\cos \pi,\sin \pi)</m> in <m>\R^2</m>. Thus we have
	that <m>(-1)(-1)</m> corresponds to 
	<me>(\cos(\pi+\pi),\sin(\pi+\pi))= (1,0)</me>
	which corresponds to the complex number 1.
	</li>
	<li>We have <m>i\leftrightarrow (\cos\pi/2,\sin\pi/2)</m>, so <m>i^2 \leftrightarrow
	(\cos \pi,\sin \pi)=(-1,0)\leftrightarrow -1</m>.
	</li>
	<li>Let <m>z\leftrightarrow P=(r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta)</m>. 
      If <m>\alpha \gt 0</m>, we have <m>\alpha\leftrightarrow
      (\alpha,0)=(\alpha \cos 0,\alpha \sin 0)</m>. By definition
      <xref ref="complexproduct"/>, we have
      <me>\alpha z \leftrightarrow
	(\alpha r\cos\theta,\alpha r\sin\theta)
	= \alpha (r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta)
	=\alpha P.</me>
      For <m>\alpha\lt 0</m>, we
      have <m>\alpha\leftrightarrow (\alpha,0)=(|\alpha| \cos \pi, |\alpha|\sin\pi)</m>, so
      <me>\alpha z \leftrightarrow
(|\alpha| r \cos(\theta+\pi),|\alpha|r\sin(\theta+\pi))
	=\alpha (r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta)
	= \alpha P.</me>
	    If <m>\alpha=0</m>, we have <m>\alpha z \leftrightarrow
              (0,0) = \alpha P</m>. In all cases, we have <m>\alpha
              z\leftrightarrow \alpha P</m>, as claimed.
	</li>
      </ol>
</p>
</commentary>

<p>
Equations <xref ref="complexsum"/> and <xref ref="complexrealscaling"/>
show how
complex addition and multiplication relate naturally to the
linear operations of addition and scaling in <m>\R^2</m>. 
More generally, complex multiplication is related to rotations of <m>\R^2</m> as
follows. For <m>z\leftrightarrow P=(r\cos \theta,r\sin \theta)</m>
and <m>w\leftrightarrow Q= (s\cos \phi,s\sin \phi)</m>, equation
<xref ref="complexproduct"/> can be expressed as
<men xml:id="complexmultisrealscalerot">zw  \leftrightarrow rR_{\theta}(Q)= sR_{\phi}(P)</men>
where <m>R_\theta,R_\phi</m> denote rotations (see <xref ref="rottransfdef"/>).
</p>

<exercise xml:id="complexmultasscalerotexer">
  <statement>
    <p>Verify <xref ref="complexmultisrealscalerot"/>.</p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="complexmultasscalerotexer"/></title>
  <p>Just write out <m>rR_{\theta}(Q)</m> and <m>sR_{\phi}(P)</m> and
    notice that both are equal to <m>rs(\cos(\theta+\phi),\sin(\theta+\phi))</m>.
  </p>
    </commentary>

 <p>
  Complex multiplication and addition obey the
  following <term>distributive law</term><idx><h>distributive law for
  complex numbers</h></idx>, for all complex numbers <m>z,u,v</m>.
  <men xml:id="complexdistlaw">z(u+v) = zu+zv</men>
 </p>

 <exercise xml:id="complexdistlawexer">
   <statement>
     <p>
     Use <xref ref="complexmultisrealscalerot"/> to verify the distributive law <xref ref="complexdistlaw"/>.  
     </p>
   </statement>
 </exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="complexdistlawexer"/></title>
  <p> Let <m>z\leftrightarrow (r\cos \theta,r\sin\theta)</m>,
    let <m>u\leftrightarrow Q</m>, and let <m>v\leftrightarrow S</m>. We
    have the following.
    <md>
      <mrow>u+v \amp \leftrightarrow Q+S</mrow>
      <mrow>z(u+v) \amp \leftrightarrow rR_\theta(Q+S) \amp \amp
      (\text{by }<xref ref="complexmultisrealscalerot"/>)
      </mrow>
      <mrow>\amp =rR_\theta(Q)+rR_\theta(S)\amp \amp (\text{linearity of
	scaling and }R_\theta)</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp \leftrightarrow zu+zv \amp \amp (\text{by }<xref ref="complexmultisrealscalerot"/>)</mrow>
    </md>

  </p>
    </commentary>


<p>Next we establish two basic ways to represent complex numbers, called
  the <term>rectangular
     form</term><idx><h>rectangular form for a complex number</h></idx> 
 (or the <term>Cartesian form</term>) and the <term>polar
     form</term><idx><h>polar form for a complex number</h></idx>.
Let <m>\expi(\theta)</m> denote the complex number that corresponds to the point
  <m>(\cos\theta,\sin\theta)</m>, and
  let <m>z\leftrightarrow (a,b)=(r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta)</m>
  with <m>r\geq 0</m>. 
  We have the following.
 <mdn>
   <mrow xml:id="rectformz">z\amp = a+bi \amp \amp (\text{rectangular form})</mrow>
   <mrow xml:id="polarformz">z\amp = rE(\theta)\amp \amp (\text{polar form})</mrow>
 </mdn>
 In particular, we have the following expression for <m>E(\theta)</m> in
 rectangular form.<fn>The function <m>E</m> is also called the "cis"
   function (for "cosine <m>i</m> sine"), implemented in many software libraries.
 </fn>
 <!--, called <term>Euler's formula</term><idx><h>Euler's formula</h>
 </idx>.-->
 <men xml:id="cisfndef">\expi(\theta)=\cos\theta + i\sin\theta</men>
   <xref ref="zxyrthetafig"/> shows a summary of the geometric content of
   the rectangular and polar forms for a complex number <m>z</m>.
</p>

    	         <figure xml:id="zxyrthetafig">
       <caption>Rectangular and polar forms for a complex number.
      </caption>
<!--            <image width="80%" source="../images/complex_rect_polar2.png"></image>-->
            <image width="80%" source="complex_rect_polar_new.png"></image>
           </figure>

 <p>
  Here is how complex addition looks in rectangular form.
 <men>(a+ib)+ (c+id)   = (a+c) + i(b+d)
 </men>
 
 Here is how complex multiplication looks in rectangular and polar
 forms.
 <mdn>
<mrow xml:id="complexmultrectangular">  (a+ib)(c+id)  \amp = (ac-bd) +
  i(ad+bc)</mrow>
<mrow xml:id="complexmultpolar">(r\expi(\theta))(s\expi(\phi)) \amp = rs\expi(\theta + \phi)</mrow>
 </mdn>
</p>

