 <exercise xml:id="complexalg2ndexer"><statement><p>Express each of the following in rectangular and
      polar form.
      <ol>
	<li> <m>3(2-i) + 6(1+i)</m></li>
	<li> <m>\left(2\expi({\pi/6})\right)\left(3\expi({-\pi/3})\right)</m></li>
	<li> <m>(2+3i)(4-i)</m></li>
	<li>	 <m>(1+i)^3</m></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

 <commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="complexalg2ndexer"/></title>
<p><ol>
	<li>	   <m>12+3i=3\sqrt{17}\;\expi({\arctan(1/4)})</m></li>
	<li>	   <m>6\expi({-\pi/6})=3\sqrt{3}-3i</m></li>
	<li>	   <m>11+10i=\sqrt{221}\;\expi({\arctan(10/11)})</m></li>
	<li>	   <m>-2+2i=2\sqrt{2}\;\expi({3\pi/4})</m></li>
      </ol>
</p>
</commentary>
 
 <p>
   Using <xref ref="complexmultpolar"/>, we have the following for <m>r\neq 0</m>.
 <men>\left(r\expi(\theta)\right)\; \left(\frac{1}{r}\expi(-\theta)\right) = 1</men>
For <m>z=r\expi(\theta)</m> with <m>r\neq 0</m>, we call <m>\frac{1}{r}\expi(-\theta)</m>
 the <term>multiplicative inverse</term><idx><h>multiplicative inverse
     of a complex number</h></idx>
  of <m>z</m>, denoted <m>{1}/{z}</m> or
 <m>z^{-1}</m>. We define the <term>quotient</term><idx><h>quotient of
 two complex numbers</h></idx>
  <m>z/w</m> or <m>\frac{z}{w}</m> by
 <men>\frac{z}{w} = zw^{-1}.</men>
 </p>


 
 <p>
   The <term>conjugate</term><idx><h>conjugate of a complex number</h></idx>
         of the complex number <m>z=x+iy=r\expi(\theta)</m>,
      denoted <m>\overline{z}</m><notation><usage><m>\overline{z}</m>
	        </usage>
     <description>conjugate of the complex number <m>z</m>
	 </description>
     </notation>
      or <m>z^\ast</m><notation><usage><m>{z}^\ast</m>
	        </usage>
     <description>conjugate of the complex number <m>z</m>
	 </description>
     </notation>, is defined to be <m>z^\ast = x-iy =
r\expi(-\theta)</m>. Geometrically, <m>z^\ast</m> is the reflection of <m>z</m> across
the real axis (the <m>x</m>-axis) in <m>\R^2</m>. Here are some relations
      involving conjugates. For all <m>z,w\in \C</m>, we have the following.
<mdn>
  <mrow xml:id="realpartformula">\re(z)  \amp  = \frac{z + z^\ast}{2}</mrow>
<mrow xml:id="imagpartformula">
  \im(z)  \amp  = \frac{z - z^\ast}{2i}</mrow>
<mrow xml:id="zzbarisnormsq">
  |z|^2  \amp  = zz^\ast</mrow>
<mrow>2\arg z  \amp  = \frac{z}{z^\ast} \;\;(\text{for } z\neq 0)</mrow>
<mrow>\frac{1}{z}
   \amp  = \frac{z^\ast}{zz^\ast}= \frac{z^\ast}{|z|^2} \;\;(\text{for } z\neq 0)</mrow>
<mrow>(zw)^\ast  \amp  = z^\ast w^\ast</mrow>
</mdn>
 </p>

 <exercise xml:id="complexdivisionexer"><statement><p>Express each of the following in rectangular and
      polar form.
      <ol>
	<li> <m>\displaystyle \frac{2+i}{3-i}</m></li>
	<li> <m>\displaystyle \frac{1+2i}{1-2i}</m></li>
	<li> <m>\displaystyle \frac{2\expi({\pi/4})}{3\expi({-\pi/2})}</m>	</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="complexdivisionexer"/></title>
  <p>
      <ol>
	<li> <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{2}i=\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\expi({\pi/4})</m></li>
	<li> <m>\displaystyle -\frac{3}{5} +\frac{4}{5}i=\expi({(\arctan(-4/3))+\pi)}</m></li>
        <li> <m>\displaystyle \frac{2}{3}\expi({3\pi/4})=-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{3} +
  \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3}i</m>	</li>
      </ol>
</p>
</commentary>
 
<exercises>

<exercise xml:id="justifyrectpolaraddmultexer"><statement><p>Verify <xref ref="rectformz"/> and
      <xref ref="polarformz"/>. That is, justify both equations
      using the definitions of complex addition and multiplication. 
      </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="justifyrectpolaraddmultexer"/></title>
<p>Let <m>z\leftrightarrow (a,b) = (r\cos
	\theta,r\sin\theta)</m>. Then we have
      <md>
	<mrow>z\amp \leftrightarrow (a,b) = a(1,0)+b(0,1)\leftrightarrow
	  a+bi</mrow>
	<mrow>z\amp \leftrightarrow (r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta) =
	r(\cos\theta,\sin\theta)\leftrightarrow rE(\theta).</mrow>
      </md>
      The rightmost double arrow "<m>\leftrightarrow</m>" in each of the
      lines above is justified by <xref ref="complexrealscaling"/>.
</p>
</commentary>

<exercise xml:id="triangleineqcomplexexer"><title>The triangle
	  inequality</title><idx><h>triangle inequality for complex numbers</h>
	</idx><statement><p>Prove the following property of norm, called
      the <em>triangle inequality</em>:
		For any two complex numbers <m>z,w</m>, we have
	  <men xml:id="triangleineqcomplex">|z+w|\leq |z|+|w|.</men>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="triangleineqcomplexexer"/></title>
  <p>
    The simplest approach is geometric:
Sketch the parallelogram for vector addition and use the fact
that the length of any side of a triangle is less than the sum of the
lengths of the other two sides.
    </p>
    <p>
  Here is one route to an algebraic proof: Let <m>z=a+bi</m>, <m>w=c+di</m>.
  Manipulate the triangle
  inequality (start by squaring both sides) to obtain 
  <me>2abcd \leq b^2c^2 + a^2d^2.</me>
  This is the same as the clearly true statement
  <me>0\leq  b^2c^2 + a^2d^2 - 2abcd = (bc-ad)^2.</me>
   Conclude by
  observing that all steps of the derivation are reversible.
</p>
</commentary>

<exercise xml:id="zzbarisnormsqexer"><statement><p>Prove <xref ref="zzbarisnormsq"/>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="zzbarisnormsqexer"/></title>
  <p>
    Let <m>z=r\expi({\theta})</m>.  Then <m>\overline{z}=r\expi({-\theta})</m>, and we
have
      <md>
	<mrow>z\overline{z} \amp  = r\expi({\theta})r\expi({-\theta})</mrow>
	<mrow>  \amp = r^2 \expi(0)</mrow>
	<mrow>  \amp  = r^2 = |z|^2.</mrow>
      </md>
</p>
</commentary>

<exercise xml:id="complexdiffnormisdistexer"><statement>Let <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> be complex numbers.  Prove that the distance
(ordinary distance between points in the plane) between <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> is
    <m>|p-q|</m>.</statement>
  <hint><p>Use rectangular form.</p>
  </hint>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="complexdiffnormisdistexer"/></title>
  <p>
    Let <m>p=a+ib</m> and <m>q=c+id</m>.
We have 
<md>
  <mrow>|p-q| \amp = |(a+ib)-(c+id)| </mrow>
  <mrow>\amp = |(a-c)+i(b-d)|</mrow>
  <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{(a-c)^2 + (b-d)^2}.</mrow>
</md>
The latter expression is the distance from <m>p</m> to <m>q</m>, so we are done.</p>
</commentary>

<exercise xml:id="realimagpartsformulaexer">
<statement>Verify the formulas <xref ref="realpartformula" /> and
  <xref ref="imagpartformula" />.
</statement>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="realimagpartsformulaexer"/></title>
<p>Let <m>z=x+iy</m>.  Then we have
<ul>
<li> <m>\displaystyle \frac{z+\overline{z}}{2}= \frac{2x}{2}=x=\re(z)</m>, and</li>
<li><m>\displaystyle
    \frac{z-\overline{z}}{2i}=\frac{2iy}{2i}=y=\im(z)</m>.</li>
</ul>
</p>
</commentary>

<exercise xml:id="twosqrootsexer"><title>Square roots</title><statement>
    <p>
      <ol><li>Given a nonzero complex number <m>z</m>, explain why <m>z</m> has exactly
	  two square roots, and explain how to find them.</li>
	<li>Solve for <m>z</m>.
	  <me> z^2= -5-16i</me>
	</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

<commentary component="instructor"><title>Instructor's solution for
<xref ref="twosqrootsexer"/></title>
  <p>
<ol><li>    Since squaring a number squares the norm and doubles the argument,
a square root can be found by taking the square root of the norm and
dividing the argument by two.  That is, for <m>z=r\expi({\theta})</m>, a square
root of <m>z</m> is <m>\sqrt{r}\expi({\theta/2})</m>.  Another square root of <m>z</m> is
the negative of that expression.  Any other square root of <m>z</m> would
have to have norm <m>\sqrt{|z|}</m> and argument <m>\theta/2</m> plus or minus an
    integer multiple of <m>\pi</m>, so these must be all the square
    roots of <m>z</m>. In symbols, the solutions to <m>w^2=z=rE(\theta)</m> are
    <me>w=\pm \sqrt{r}E(\theta/2).</me>
  </li>
  <li><m>\pm 281^{1/4}E\left(\frac{\arctan(16/5)+\pi}{2}\right)</m>
  </li>
</ol>
</p>
</commentary>

